<i>2015 Parliamentary Inspection by Environment and Labor Committee</i>

37
00:03:07,330 --> 00:03:10,510
See this, okay? See this right now.

38
00:03:10,510 --> 00:03:13,030
These are the numbers showing marine pollution

39
00:03:13,030 --> 00:03:15,340
due to the industrial wastewater in Gyeongje City.

40
00:03:15,340 --> 00:03:18,270
Look, in BOD from 5

41
00:03:18,270 --> 00:03:23,170
to 16.4, 4.5 to 18.95 in COD. Take a look!

42
00:03:23,170 --> 00:03:26,850
How many times is this!

43
00:03:26,850 --> 00:03:29,650
Are you going to kill them all?

44
00:03:29,650 --> 00:03:31,810
Are you crazy?!

45
00:03:31,810 --> 00:03:34,530
What are you doing not managing these things!

46
00:03:34,530 --> 00:03:37,290
Are you going to kill everyone in Gyeongje City?

47
00:03:38,610 --> 00:03:41,560
Don't touch the glasses!

48
00:03:41,560 --> 00:03:46,870
I'll give this to you, so take it home and study it.

49
00:03:46,870 --> 00:03:48,690
Take a very careful look.

50
00:03:48,690 --> 00:03:53,450
Frame it, put it up on the wall and study it everyday.

51
00:03:55,390 --> 00:03:58,110
Play it, Secretary Park.

52
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:10,620
A group of experts, my staff and I

53
00:04:10,620 --> 00:04:15,150
personally went down to Gyeongje River and tested the water quality.

54
00:04:15,150 --> 00:04:18,450
Our Director of Korea Water Quality Management Company, take a look.

55
00:04:19,110 --> 00:04:21,870
Take a good look. Is that a river now?

56
00:04:21,870 --> 00:04:23,390
Huh?

57
00:04:23,390 --> 00:04:27,260
Does that look like a river? What do you see?

58
00:04:27,260 --> 00:04:29,690
Does it seem like sewage water?

59
00:04:29,690 --> 00:04:33,890
Do you think that was pumped from a septic tank?

60
00:04:33,890 --> 00:04:38,970
That is none other than the Gyeongje River. The current Gyeongje River where all fishes have died out!

61
00:04:38,970 --> 00:04:43,310
Huh?! What are you going to do about it?

62
00:04:43,310 --> 00:04:47,710
What are you going to do about all those fishes? You hurry and revive them now!

63
00:04:48,460 --> 00:04:50,250
Moving on to the next one.

64
00:04:51,790 --> 00:04:55,010
Do you see that, huh?

65
00:04:55,950 --> 00:04:59,370
Are you tending a green tea field in the river, now?

66
00:04:59,370 --> 00:05:03,290
Green tea field, green tea field? What are you going to do?

67
00:05:03,290 --> 00:05:06,190
What kind of management work are you doing, seriously!

68
00:05:08,430 --> 00:05:12,570
Stop fidgeting with your glasses. Why do you, why...

69
00:05:14,140 --> 00:05:19,000
I even personally brought a sample.

70
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:26,200
Do you see this? I thought you might not believe it. I didn't put anything in it, I just ladled this out, personally.

71
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:28,650
Taste it.

72
00:05:30,050 --> 00:05:33,860
Here, this too. You are getting plenty today.

73
00:05:40,590 --> 00:05:43,130
Why are we not prepared?

74
00:05:43,130 --> 00:05:45,130
Are you sticking it to me?

75
00:05:45,130 --> 00:05:50,150
From tomorrow until the end of the parliamentary inspection, prepare all questionnaires like that. Go back to your seat.

76
00:05:51,310 --> 00:05:56,880
Only my aides can do it. Not everyone is capable of that.

77
00:05:56,880 --> 00:06:03,310
And do you admit this levee construction in Gyeongje City was done shoddily?

78
00:06:03,310 --> 00:06:04,530
It wasn't shoddy work.

79
00:06:04,530 --> 00:06:07,710
Not shoddy work? Are you sure?

80
00:06:07,710 --> 00:06:12,770
You can get punished for perjury during a parliamentary inspection. Don't you know?

81
00:06:12,770 --> 00:06:17,910
Seeing how you're touching your glasses, it is a lie. Fine.

82
00:06:17,910 --> 00:06:21,770
I will read you all of the materials I prepared.

83
00:06:22,490 --> 00:06:28,190
First... Ah, ah, ah. Chairwoman, please give me more time.

84
00:06:28,190 --> 00:06:32,170
Enough already. Other assemblymen have to question too.

85
00:06:32,170 --> 00:06:35,590
But I have to do everything I prepared. When I came with this much preparation...

86
00:06:35,590 --> 00:06:38,530
If you do everything at the beginning, what does that make us?

87
00:06:38,530 --> 00:06:42,450
Are you the only one doing the parliamentary inspection? When we've prepared as much as you?

88
00:06:42,450 --> 00:06:45,560
Wow, between fellow party members, you're so petty.

89
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:52,760
Assemblyman Jin, I will give you my five minutes of additional question time. Use that.

90
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:58,560
Aigo, thank you, Assemblywoman Cheon! Aigo, thank you.

91
00:06:59,290 --> 00:07:03,240
Did you see that? When even an opposition party assemblywoman is like that?

92
00:07:05,450 --> 00:07:08,260
But please give it to me quickly, the 5 minutes?

93
00:07:12,510 --> 00:07:13,980
Oh, it's working well.

94
00:07:13,980 --> 00:07:18,020
Witness, from now on, to the questions I ask

95
00:07:18,020 --> 00:07:20,860
answer in no uncertain terms. Understand?

96
00:07:20,860 --> 00:07:24,080
Aren't you really going to submit the materials?

97
00:07:24,080 --> 00:07:28,740
Don't you know this is against the Board of Audit and Inspection Act?

98
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:31,700
What? A meal?

99
00:07:33,820 --> 00:07:37,820
That place's taste has changed, unlike the good old times. But I know...

100
00:07:40,490 --> 00:07:45,380
Now, did I ask for a meal or materials? It's not like I'm going around hungry.

101
00:07:45,380 --> 00:07:48,760
Send them to me by midnight. Hang up.

102
00:07:49,740 --> 00:07:52,980
But what do they take an aide for?

103
00:07:54,510 --> 00:07:56,380
Rain, rain. Eat the rain man.

104
00:07:56,380 --> 00:07:58,160
Which one do I eat? Which one?

105
00:07:58,160 --> 00:08:01,480
Of course you have to eat ssangpi. That's right!

106
00:08:01,480 --> 00:08:03,540
Rain ssangpi.

107
00:08:04,440 --> 00:08:06,740
That's right.

108
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:09,900
What are you doing?

109
00:08:10,940 --> 00:08:15,860
I'm just taking a breather from making press materials.

110
00:08:15,860 --> 00:08:18,500
I'm going to go to Aide Choi and tell on you.

111
00:08:22,620 --> 00:08:24,500
It's fun, right? Right?

112
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:28,620
So much fun. You can't lose the money I've won.

113
00:08:28,620 --> 00:08:31,040
I got it, I got it.

114
00:08:31,040 --> 00:08:34,540
Just because they don't have to work on questionnaires, they are being too much.

115
00:08:38,980 --> 00:08:39,860
Yes, why?

116
00:08:39,860 --> 00:08:42,000
<i>Environment and Labor Committee<br>Meeting Room</i>

117
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:46,700
Aide Seo, you did write a questionnaire to support companies with innovative environmental technologies, right?

118
00:08:46,700 --> 00:08:49,160
Yes, but why?

119
00:08:49,160 --> 00:08:52,320
But the Assemblyman does not have it.

120
00:08:52,320 --> 00:08:54,000
What did you say?

121
00:08:56,240 --> 00:08:59,160
When I worked so hard to make this questionnaire,

122
00:08:59,160 --> 00:09:00,920
how can you take this out?

123
00:09:00,920 --> 00:09:03,520
It does not fit the tone of the Assemblyman's legislative activities.

124
00:09:03,520 --> 00:09:08,840
But that the government should give some support to companies that come up with cutting-edge new technologies...

125
00:09:08,840 --> 00:09:11,380
Why does that not fit the Assemblyman's tone?

126
00:09:11,380 --> 00:09:13,760
It does not fit.

127
00:09:13,760 --> 00:09:18,780
Look here, Aide Choi. Even though you're the senior aide, this is exceeding your authority.

128
00:09:18,780 --> 00:09:21,760
I'm in charge of questionnaires.

129
00:09:23,400 --> 00:09:28,000
I was not going to bring this up, but

130
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:33,440
that questionnaire. Didn't a new technology company solicit you to write it?

131
00:09:34,360 --> 00:09:38,080
What? What do you take me for...

132
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:42,220
Special interest legislation after getting lobbied for it, that is not the only evil thing.

133
00:09:42,220 --> 00:09:46,760
Making special interest questionnaires like this one after getting solicitations, that practice also has to disappear!

134
00:09:47,620 --> 00:09:52,260
Since the Assemblyman does not know about this, be careful not to repeat this sort of thing in the future.

135
00:09:53,460 --> 00:09:59,230
What do you mean the Assemblyman doesn't know? Do you even know who that company owner is?

136
00:09:59,230 --> 00:10:04,120
- Who?<br>- President Lee Taek Jo of SOI.

137
00:10:04,120 --> 00:10:05,080
Lee Taek Jo?

138
00:10:05,080 --> 00:10:09,680
I mean that $5000 designer watch that almost cost Secretary Kim his job...

139
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:11,880
The person who gave that.

140
00:10:11,880 --> 00:10:14,880
The Assemblyman returned that watch.

141
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:17,240
Who returned what now?

142
00:10:17,240 --> 00:10:19,700
When the giver says he didn't get it back.

143
00:10:19,700 --> 00:10:23,340
- What?<br>- How could I stick it out without writing him that questionnaire?

144
00:10:23,340 --> 00:10:27,320
<i>Give it to me. I will return it to President Lee.</i>

145
00:10:27,320 --> 00:10:31,260
<i>It's okay. The punk who received it must return it.</i>

146
00:10:33,960 --> 00:10:37,960
Parliamentary inspection is no small job.

147
00:10:37,960 --> 00:10:39,740
Really...

148
00:10:39,740 --> 00:10:43,480
Aide Choi, get me Assemblywoman Hong Chan Mi's address.

149
00:10:43,480 --> 00:10:44,760
So I can try to see her.

150
00:10:44,760 --> 00:10:47,680
Give me an honest answer to the question I'm about to ask.

151
00:10:47,680 --> 00:10:49,900
Why are you like this again all of a sudden? What is it?

152
00:10:49,900 --> 00:10:54,000
What did you do with that designer watch you had received from President Lee Taek Jo?

153
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:57,780
I got cash for it and bought bread for homeless people.

154
00:10:57,780 --> 00:10:59,460
Don't joke around!

155
00:10:59,460 --> 00:11:01,420
I'm not joking.

156
00:11:01,420 --> 00:11:02,640
You are not joking?

157
00:11:02,640 --> 00:11:05,100
If you don't believe me, ask Gyu Hwan.

158
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:07,880
He worked like a dog for several days because of that.

159
00:11:07,880 --> 00:11:11,080
Didn't you say you exchange emails everyday?

160
00:11:22,490 --> 00:11:24,690
Why don't you just confess?

161
00:11:24,690 --> 00:11:27,130
From a trustworthy source,

162
00:11:27,130 --> 00:11:31,690
we got very detailed information about your involvement in the delivery of the bribe before summoning you.

163
00:11:33,510 --> 00:11:39,310
<i>Because I was not convinced by Chief Secretary Lim's transcript alone,</i>

164
00:11:39,310 --> 00:11:44,110
<i>I put temptation in the Assemblyman's way.</i>

165
00:11:48,870 --> 00:11:54,470
Pleading the fifth, may get you left holding the bag.

166
00:11:58,490 --> 00:12:03,370
Fine. Why don't you just leave for today?

167
00:12:22,270 --> 00:12:24,710
Take out money from the Assemblyman's salary

168
00:12:24,710 --> 00:12:28,370
tomorrow and buy the exact same watch as the one President Lee gave.

169
00:12:28,370 --> 00:12:29,150
Okay.

170
00:12:29,150 --> 00:12:31,670
Forget it, why do that?

171
00:12:31,670 --> 00:12:33,840
You stay quiet, Assemblyman.

172
00:12:33,840 --> 00:12:38,340
Clearly you have violated the Political Funds Act.

173
00:12:40,480 --> 00:12:42,320
But, just...

174
00:12:42,320 --> 00:12:45,110
It's just, it's okay.

175
00:12:45,110 --> 00:12:48,940
If I had that kind of money, I'd rather buy my Joo Hee some clothes.

176
00:12:48,940 --> 00:12:51,280
Would it have been any better to do that?

177
00:12:51,280 --> 00:12:54,860
Are you some sort of a benevolent thief who robs from the rich to give to the poor?

178
00:12:54,860 --> 00:12:56,620
Why did you buy homeless people bread, why?

179
00:12:56,620 --> 00:13:00,020
Then, should I have bought those people in poor health alcohol? Of course I should have bought them bread.

180
00:13:00,020 --> 00:13:02,060
Assemblyman!

181
00:13:02,060 --> 00:13:06,320
I am sorry. At that time, I did not know

182
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:08,900
that things would get this serious.

183
00:13:08,900 --> 00:13:13,380
You just try this one more time. Then, I'm really going to cane you.

184
00:13:13,380 --> 00:13:15,640
Me too.

185
00:13:20,840 --> 00:13:24,970
7769? Call.

186
00:13:26,460 --> 00:13:27,570
<i>Who is it?</i>

187
00:13:27,570 --> 00:13:33,430
Oh, hello. I am Assemblyman Jin Sang Pil, the People's Spoilsport who always tries his best.

188
00:13:33,430 --> 00:13:36,250
Is Assemblywoman Hong home, by any chance?

189
00:13:36,250 --> 00:13:37,830
<i>No, she is not.</i>

190
00:13:37,830 --> 00:13:42,290
Oh, really? Then, do you by any chance know where...

191
00:13:42,290 --> 00:13:44,100
Hello?

192
00:13:44,100 --> 00:13:46,060
Hello!

193
00:13:46,060 --> 00:13:48,400
What the...

194
00:13:48,400 --> 00:13:52,720
Does this run in her family? Why hang up so suddenly?

195
00:13:52,720 --> 00:13:55,120
Seriously...

196
00:14:00,580 --> 00:14:05,680
Yes, this is Assemblyman Jin Sang Pil, the People's Spoilsport who always tries his best.

197
00:14:05,680 --> 00:14:06,980
Assemblyman.

198
00:14:06,980 --> 00:14:09,380
Oh,

199
00:14:09,380 --> 00:14:11,070
it's you, Gyu Hwan.

200
00:14:11,070 --> 00:14:12,210
Yes.

201
00:14:12,210 --> 00:14:14,050
Okay,

202
00:14:15,230 --> 00:14:16,750
have you been well?

203
00:14:16,750 --> 00:14:20,310
Where are you right now?

204
00:14:20,310 --> 00:14:22,290
Hey, punk, while an elder is

205
00:14:22,290 --> 00:14:25,190
greeting you, how can you abruptly ask for the whereabouts?

206
00:14:25,190 --> 00:14:27,270
Punk, do you really want to get some beating?

207
00:14:27,270 --> 00:14:28,490
I said where are you!

208
00:14:28,490 --> 00:14:32,270
I am out to meet someone, happy, punk?

209
00:14:32,270 --> 00:14:34,550
I would like to see you now.

210
00:14:34,550 --> 00:14:36,710
Now?

211
00:14:38,950 --> 00:14:42,090
- Gyu Hwan, let's meet at home.<br>- Assemblyman!

212
00:14:42,090 --> 00:14:47,540
I'll get home soon, so let's meet at home in a little bit. I've got to go.

213
00:14:59,620 --> 00:15:02,280
Assemblywoman Hong!

214
00:15:09,960 --> 00:15:12,970
How can an assemblywoman not come to the Assembly?

215
00:15:12,970 --> 00:15:15,670
Because you are not even showing your face in the inspection hearings,

216
00:15:15,670 --> 00:15:21,130
reporters and NGOs are up in arms about that, do you know that?

217
00:15:21,130 --> 00:15:24,410
I am prepared to be reviled.

218
00:15:24,410 --> 00:15:28,390
During my press conference to announce my resignation, I will return my salary

219
00:15:28,400 --> 00:15:30,600
and apologize to the people.

220
00:15:30,600 --> 00:15:34,070
Are you really going to resign?

221
00:15:36,110 --> 00:15:36,830
Yes.

222
00:15:36,830 --> 00:15:39,950
No, don't do that. Just join Indifferent-to-BH faction.

223
00:15:39,950 --> 00:15:41,520
I will be good to you.

224
00:15:41,520 --> 00:15:46,040
I guess you're mistaken because I opposed your expulsion.

225
00:15:46,040 --> 00:15:49,480
But at that time, just out of embarrassment...

226
00:15:50,980 --> 00:15:54,480
I did that because I didn't want to be embarrassed.

227
00:15:54,480 --> 00:15:58,220
It's okay if you do not join Indifferent-to-BH faction.

228
00:15:58,220 --> 00:16:02,220
But isn't quitting the Assembly too much?

229
00:16:02,220 --> 00:16:04,360
When the people put you there.

230
00:16:04,360 --> 00:16:06,580
The people

231
00:16:07,640 --> 00:16:09,360
put me there?

232
00:16:09,360 --> 00:16:11,360
Of course.

233
00:16:13,420 --> 00:16:15,400
No.

234
00:16:15,400 --> 00:16:19,520
I was just the newest model...

235
00:16:20,560 --> 00:16:22,400
the brand-new latest product.

236
00:16:22,400 --> 00:16:24,420
What, newest? A new model?

237
00:16:24,420 --> 00:16:27,720
During the general election 4 years ago,

238
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:31,780
displayed in a window of the shop called the Gookmin Party,

239
00:16:31,780 --> 00:16:36,780
the latest item with a glitzy design but of unproven quality!

240
00:16:36,780 --> 00:16:39,680
That was Hong Chan Mi.

241
00:16:39,680 --> 00:16:41,990
Why do you torment yourself like that?

242
00:16:41,990 --> 00:16:45,550
What's wrong with you, when you are pretty and smart?

243
00:16:45,550 --> 00:16:49,290
You talk well. You're diligent.

244
00:16:50,350 --> 00:16:53,110
It's just your personality that is a bit...

245
00:16:55,250 --> 00:16:59,790
When I was selected as a proportional representative and entered the Assembly with high expectations

246
00:16:59,790 --> 00:17:04,330
I heard the words the staff and reporters were whispering behind my back.

247
00:17:04,330 --> 00:17:06,470
What did they say?

